76561198049105119,Recommended,225300,8896466,"Posted: 28 January, 2014",all,Amarysse,"My 10-year-old self and I can't recommend this game enough. It's classic puzzle-solving at its finest. In fact I'm pretty sure that playing it made me smarter. There's no AI holding your hand here, nor any obnoxious button graphics that flash on-screen and yell at you to mash the Y key to perform some entirely gimmicky and circumstantial roundhouse backflip to the face that you'll never need to do again. Just Lara and her lovably awkward polygons running straight ahead with the arms fully stretched out at a stiff, perpendicular angle to the body. On occasion, you can make her say ""No,"" in a charming British voice, over and over again, and then kill her in a variety of exciting ways.Serously though, the levels are rendered beautifully, leaving just the right amount to the imagination, and many of the puzzles actually require more than three brain cells to figure out. There are no journal entries offering fluff faux ""immersion,"" no toggled map overlays to tell you where you are, and very little clues to help you out - just you and an often convoluted and action-packed pathway from the start of a level to the exit. The levels themselves, especially the memorable Venice series, have personality and often make you feel real suspense and a sense of danger. While some puzzles might frustrate the modern gamer (certain ones depend on very exact placement of Lara to perform a series of jumps with no room for error, for instance, which can get pretty tedious), the feeling of accomplishment you get after finally landing that horrendous jump, or opening that goddamn door, is so worth the effort.In my opinion, this and the original Tomb Raider are the best installments in the series, mostly thanks to their simplicity. What it lacks in modern graphics, the game makes up for tenfold in gameplay and creativity of story and design. Plus, for the first time, Lara gets to use vehicles, which add a great deal of fun to the levels they appear in, by which I mean you can drive them off cliffs and explode.All in all, you won't regret giving this a try. Yeah, you'll probably laugh at Lara and make fun of the dated graphics, and swear loudly at the controls, but these days, that's part of the fun. Definitely a must for 90s action/adventure gaming fans and especially people who don't mind video games not insulting their intelligence for a change.Oh and you can lock the butler in the freezer."
,Recommended,225300,9510649,"Posted: 17 March, 2014",all,bull,"One of the best adventure games of all times. And i am aware that nowadays we have adventure games with impressive graphics or with great storylines, with vast areas to explore, games that offer addictive gameplay, and i love those too(i also like the  TR reboot, for example). But as wierd as it may sound, nothing beats the feeling of swan-diving through a small gap in the middle of a lava lake into a pond that lays directly under that lava. While on today`s standards, TR2 may not be quite an ""eye candy"", it compensates with some great level designs, and it sure offers great gameplay, making the player to put some effort in order to complete the game."
76561198060028099,Recommended,225300,7786036,"Posted: 27 November, 2013",all,くそｃｒｘニガー,"Tomb Raider II is an outstanding game for all the Classic Fans of the Tomb Raider Franchise. I owned it when I was younger, but never beat it. Now that its on Steam, I finally had the chance to. When you are dropped off in China for the first time, the graphics may not be so impressive, but for a game from 1998, its pretty nice. Throughout the game, I only really had 2 problems. This game, compared to Tomb Raider I, is more fighting oriented and is ""overflowed' by the amounts of combat (Human-to-Human). In Tomb Raider I, you fought around 10 people, all of them being reoccuring characters in the storyline. My second problem was how excessively long the Shipwreck stages were. They should of decreased the amount of Shipwreck level, and should have added a new set of stages. 90/100. Gameplay 10/10. Graphics 9/10. Storyline 9/10. Badass...11/10 If you're a diehard Tomb Raider fan, or just somebody looking for a nice action/ adventure game, Tomb Raider II is right for you."
76561198119731825,Recommended,225300,24409122,"Posted: 19 July, 2016",all,☑ Verified Noob [inactive],"My favourite classic Tomb Raider!Why?- Amazing and awesome levels,- VARIOUS levels,- amazing story,- first animated hair and first mobile source of light (flares),- many cool ideas packed into those levels,- very nice FMVs (movie clips with hi-poly models),- many cut-scenes,- amazing music, some those memorable notes which defined TR music,- a big training map (house & garden) available anytime,- an old servant thanks to who Lara was never thirsty (unless frozen :>),- first usable vehicles (boat & snowmobile),- various enemies (human, animals, fantasy creatures) with various weapons,- those moments when the music changed and you discovered new part of the map and you said ""WOW!"",- those some moments when you was going to s##t your pants (remember those loud howls&roars chasing you in the winter level?),- some nice FANTASY included (the dragon story, the Floating Islands map)...I simply love that part!Level sizes are JUST RIGHT in that part and they found a golden mean between the fight and the exploration!And an important thing many kids forget about. Expensive computers in that era were only capable to play (NOT encode) two MP3 320kbit/s files in realtime and do nothing more. And TR2 creators did such a great 3D game with audio for those computers and overcame those limitations...I believe it was still the moment when great ideas were involved to make the game even more fun!I bought mine game with the TR Collection and I am satisfied.There is a level editor (TRLE) for TR2, available for free! There are many fan-made custom levels for TR2! Those levels are often provided as a full games ready-to-run, but when installing those maps into the Steam game you will get the TR2 music.For Geeks: You can also use the fly-patch as it is compatible with the Steam version and is NOT compatible with the version provided with many custom levels. The fly-patch does NOT mess multiplayer experience as there are no multiplayer in TR2, but this is an unnoficial cheating hack and use it only at your own risk. It may break the gameplay experience and I do not recommend it unless you already did the whole game. You can also find 16:9, 16:10 and 5:4 widescreen support patch. Use only trusted sources and scan patcher files for malware before launching them!TR2 Steam community posted many info about HD textures pack, controller configurations, walkthroughts, etc.BTW: TR2 had the campfire visible in first level... :>DISCLAIMER: If you are 2000+ era, you may not feel like we did in 90s. You may blame a complete lack of mouse support. You may blame tank controls (but Lara does sideways when jumping). You may blame slow movement animations which created that game playable on those computers (we wereveryhappy when having 5FPS in 640x480; well... we played so often using 320x240 back then...).But they are NOT real cons of that game. This is how games were designed back then for those hardware components (mostly no GPU, slow CPU, 4:3 CRT monitor and a ball-mouse).You may miss all those 125 hint arrows per level, glowing items and a voice which is constantly telling you what you should do in that room, butthis iswhy we love those old classics and why we spent a part of our life there without getting bored. Sometimes there is a graphics bug with shadows and you will be forced to live with it, to find a fix or to switch to software renderer (add ""-setup"" to launch options to invoke the setup window). IMHO if you are still curious and wanna try Classic TRs, buy TR Collection. You will get so many games including: TR1, TR2, TR Anniversary (modern TR1) up to TR2013 with DLCs which has great graphics, cute Lara model and a tiny, but great multiplayer community."
