76561198273600642,Recommended,225300,24522343,"Posted: 25 July, 2016",all,TombRaider99,"Tomb Raider has always been one of my favourite game series'. I first joined the series when I was five or so and AoD had just been released. Despite that game being considered a low point in the series I loved it. To me there was something about Lara, something about her adventures and the history mixed with mythology that made them unique.Tomb Raider II was, and still is I might add, considered a high point for the series. Not only due to the commercial success it experienced almost twenty years ago but because of everything about it. The game was in 3d which at the time was not really a thing, save for Mario 64, and not only that but it feautured an awesome protagonist, an awesome story and very good graphics for the time. Sure it may not hold up today but it is definitely a game worth revisiting for long time fans of the series or a game worth discovering for people who were drawn in due to the 2013 reboot of the series.The plot follows Lara one year after the first game as she seacrhes for an ancient Chinese dagger said to possess the powers of a dragon to whomever plunges it into their chest. This search takes her all over the world, from China to Venice and beyond. Along the way you will experience fun, and sometimes challenging, platforming, fight all sorts of enemies from feeble spiders to mythalogical monsters. If you don't want to follow the main story right away or you maybe want a refresher course in the controls you can always visit Laras home: Croft Manor. It features an assault course, a hedge maze, various rooms and you can lock her butler Winston in the fridge so, you know, the usual for the classic tomb raider games.Whether you are new to the series or are revisiting it, this is definitely a game worth buying and really what do you have to lose? It's very cheap on steam and virtually everywhere else. However, I must say that it does take a while to get back into the controls which are a little clucky by modern standards but once you do it fits like an old glove."
